      "source": [
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a temporary DataFrame to get the 'before' interpolation state\n",
        "# This is necessary because the main 'df' has already been interpolated.\n",
        "df_before_interpolation = pd.read_csv(\"/content/machine_logs.csv\")\n",
        "df_before_interpolation['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df_before_interpolation['timestamp'], format=\"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\")\n",
        "df_before_interpolation = df_before_interpolation.sort_values(\"timestamp\")\n",
        "df_before_interpolation = df_before_interpolation.set_index(\"timestamp\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a figure with two subplots\n",
        "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 7))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot 'BEFORE Interpolation' on the first subplot\n",
        "df_before_interpolation['sensor_temp_c'].plot(ax=axes[0], title=\"Temperature BEFORE Interpolation\", alpha=0.7)\n",
        "axes[0].set_xlabel(\"Timestamp\")\n",
        "axes[0].set_ylabel(\"Temperature (C)\")\n",
        "axes[0].grid(True)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot 'AFTER Interpolation' on the second subplot\n",
        "df['sensor_temp_c'].plot(ax=axes[1], title=\"Temperature AFTER Interpolation\")\n",
        "axes[1].set_xlabel(\"Timestamp\")\n",
        "axes[1].set_ylabel(\"Temperature (C)\")\n",
        "axes[1].grid(True)\n",
        "\n",

      "source": [
        "Missing temperature values (~5%) were handled using time-based interpolation to preserve temporal continuity and physical realism. Mean or median imputation was avoided as it would distort trend-based failure signals."
